    AI Overview
    Learn more
    Diabetes is a chronic condition where the body has difficulty regulating blood sugar (glucose) levels, either because it doesn't produce enough insulin, or the body can't effectively use the insulin it produces. 
    Here's a more detailed explanation: 
    What is Diabetes?
    • Chronic Condition:
      Diabetes is a long-term condition that affects how your body uses glucose (sugar) for energy. 
    • Insulin's Role:
      Insulin is a hormone produced by the pancreas that helps glucose enter the body's cells to be used for energy. 
    • Types of Diabetes:
      • Type 1 Diabetes: The body's immune system mistakenly attacks and destroys the insulin-producing cells in the pancreas. 
      • Type 2 Diabetes: The body becomes resistant to insulin, or doesn't produce enough insulin to maintain normal blood sugar levels. 
      • Gestational Diabetes: Develops during pregnancy, but usually resolves after childbirth. 
    • High Blood Sugar (Hyperglycemia):
      In diabetes, glucose builds up in the blood instead of being used by the cells, leading to high blood sugar levels. 
    • Long-Term Complications:
      Uncontrolled high blood sugar can damage blood vessels and nerves, leading to serious health problems like heart disease, kidney disease, nerve damage, and vision loss. 
    Symptoms of Diabetes:
    • Excessive thirst and urination
    • Unexplained weight loss (especially in type 1 diabetes)
    • Increased hunger
    • Fatigue
    • Blurred vision
    • Slow-healing wounds
    • Frequent infections 
    Diagnosis:
    • Blood Tests: Healthcare providers diagnose diabetes by checking blood glucose levels through various tests. 
      • Fasting Plasma Glucose Test: Measures blood sugar after an overnight fast. 
      • Random Plasma Glucose Test: Measures blood sugar at any time, regardless of when you last ate. 
      • A1C Test (HbA1c): Provides an average of your blood sugar levels over the past 2-3 months. 
    • Other Tests: The Mayo Clinic recommends glucose tolerance tests may also be used. 
    Treatment and Management:
    • Lifestyle Changes:
      Diet and exercise can help manage blood sugar levels, especially in type 2 diabetes. 
    • Medications:
      Insulin injections or other medications may be needed to control blood sugar levels. 
    • Regular Monitoring:
      People with diabetes need to regularly monitor their blood sugar levels to ensure they are within a healthy range. 
    • Education and Support:
      The CDC recommends working with a healthcare team to develop a personalized diabetes management plan. 
    • Prevention:
      The Mayo Clinic recommends healthy lifestyle choices, such as maintaining a healthy weight, eating a balanced diet, and engaging in regular physical activity, can help prevent type 2 diabetes.

      What are 10 warning signs of diabetes?
      AI Overview
      Ten potential warning signs of diabetes include frequent urination, excessive thirst, unexplained weight loss, constant hunger, extreme fatigue, blurry vision, slow-healing wounds, frequent infections, tingling or numbness in hands/feet, and dry skin. 
      Here's a more detailed look at these warning signs:
      • Frequent urination (especially at night):
        Your kidneys are working overtime to filter out excess sugar from your blood, leading to increased urination. 
      • Excessive thirst:
        As your body tries to flush out the excess sugar, it loses fluids, leading to dehydration and increased thirst. 
      • Unexplained weight loss:
        Despite increased hunger, your body may not be able to use the glucose for energy, leading to weight loss. 
      • Constant hunger:
        Your body may not be able to properly use the glucose for energy, leading to a constant feeling of hunger. 
      • Extreme fatigue:
        The body's inability to use glucose for energy can lead to persistent tiredness and weakness. 
      • Blurry vision:
        High blood sugar levels can damage the small blood vessels in the eyes, leading to blurry vision. 
      • Slow-healing wounds:
        High blood sugar levels can impair circulation and wound healing. 
      • Frequent infections:
        High blood sugar can weaken the immune system, making you more susceptible to infections. 
      • Tingling or numbness in hands/feet:
        High blood sugar can damage nerves, leading to tingling, numbness, or pain in the extremities. 
      • Dry skin:
        Dehydration from increased urination and high blood sugar can lead to dry and itchy skin.

        What foods should diabetics avoid?
        AI Overview
        To manage diabetes effectively, individuals should limit or avoid foods high in added sugars, refined carbohydrates, saturated and trans fats, and excessive sodium, as well as sugary drinks and processed foods. 
        Here's a more detailed breakdown of foods to limit or avoid:
        Foods High in Added Sugars:
        • Sugary drinks: Soda, juice, sports drinks, and energy drinks. 
        • Candy, cookies, cakes, ice cream, and sweetened cereals: These are high in simple carbohydrates that can cause rapid spikes in blood sugar. 
        • Canned fruits with added sugar: Opt for unsweetened or naturally sweetened options. 
        • Sweetened coffee and tea beverages 
        Refined Carbohydrates:
        • White bread, white rice, and white pasta: These lack fiber and nutrients, leading to rapid blood sugar increases. 
        • Pastries and other baked goods made with refined flour: These are often high in simple carbohydrates and unhealthy fats. 
        • Refined breakfast cereals 
        Unhealthy Fats:
        • Fried foods:
          These are high in saturated and trans fats, which can negatively impact heart health and insulin resistance. 
        • Full-fat dairy products:
          While dairy can be part of a healthy diet, choose low-fat or non-fat options to reduce saturated fat intake. 
        • Processed meats:
          Limit consumption of bacon, ham, sausages, and other processed meats, which can be high in unhealthy fats and sodium. 
        • Animal fats:
          Reduce consumption of fatty meats and replace them with lean protein sources like fish and poultry. 
        Other Foods to Limit:
        • Excessive sodium (salt): High sodium intake can contribute to high blood pressure, a common complication of diabetes. 
        • Alcohol: If you choose to drink, do so in moderation. 
        • Highly processed foods: These often contain added sugars, unhealthy fats, and sodium, and lack essential nutrients. 
        • Foods high in energy such as take away foods, sweet biscuits, cakes, sugar sweetened drinks and fruit juice, lollies, chocolate and savoury snacks 
        Instead of these foods, consider:
        • Non-starchy vegetables: Broccoli, spinach, lettuce, and other non-starchy vegetables are low in carbohydrates and high in nutrients. 
        • Fruits: Choose whole fruits instead of fruit juices, which can be high in sugar. 
        • Whole grains: Opt for whole wheat bread, brown rice, and other whole grain products, which are higher in fiber than refined grains. 
        • Lean protein sources: Chicken, fish, beans, and lentils are good sources of protein that won't spike blood sugar. 
        • Healthy fats: Choose unsaturated fats like olive oil, avocados, and nuts.

          How does diabetes affect your life?
          About diabetes – long-term effects

          Over time, high blood glucose levels can damage the body's organs. Possible long-term effects include damage to large (macrovascular) and small (microvascular) blood vessels, which can lead to heart attack, stroke, and problems with the kidneys, eyes, gums, feet and nerves.

          What is a diabetic blood sugar level?
          AI Overview
          For people with diabetes, target blood sugar levels are generally 80 to 130 mg/dL (4.4 to 7.2 mmol/L) before meals and less than 180 mg/dL (10.0 mmol/L) two hours after meals. 
          Here's a more detailed breakdown:
          Normal Blood Sugar Levels:
          • Fasting (before eating): 70 to 99 mg/dL (3.9 to 5.5 mmol/L) 
          • Non-fasting (random): Less than 125 mg/dL (6.9 mmol/L) 
          Prediabetes:
          • Fasting: 100 to 125 mg/dL (5.6 to 6.9 mmol/L)
          • A1C: 5.7% to 6.4% 
          Diabetes:
          • Fasting: 126 mg/dL (7.0 mmol/L) or higher on two separate tests
          • A1C: 6.5% or higher 
          Target Blood Sugar Levels for People with Diabetes:
          • Before meals: 80 to 130 mg/dL (4.4 to 7.2 mmol/L)
          • Two hours after meals: Less than 180 mg/dL (10.0 mmol/L)
          • A1C: Below 7% (ideally below 6.5%) 
          Important Notes:
          • Individualized Targets:
            Target blood sugar levels can vary depending on individual factors, such as age, overall health, and type of diabetes. 
          • Regular Monitoring:
            Regular blood sugar monitoring is crucial for people with diabetes to help manage their condition effectively. 
          • Consult with a Healthcare Professional:
            It's essential to discuss blood sugar targets and monitoring with a healthcare professional to determine the best approach for individual needs. 
          • Hypoglycemia:
            Low blood sugar (hypoglycemia), typically below 70 mg/dL (3.9 mmol/L), can be dangerous and requires immediate treatment. 
          • Hyperglycemia:
            High blood sugar (hyperglycemia) can lead to serious health complications if left unmanaged.

            Complementary results

            Diabetes
            Also called: diabetes mellitus
            A group of diseases that result in too much sugar in the blood (high blood glucose).
            Most common types
            Type 2 diabetes
            A chronic condition that affects the way the body processes blood sugar (glucose).
            Type 1 diabetes
            A chronic condition in which the pancreas produces little or no insulin.
            Prediabetes
            A condition in which blood sugar is high, but not high enough to be type 2 diabetes.
            Gestational diabetes
            A form of high blood sugar affecting pregnant women.
            For informational purposes only. Consult your local medical authority for advice.
